<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="432" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,793,1918]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,793,818]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[306,375,793,818]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Head.</emphasis>
Antennae sub-quadripectinate (longly bipectinate with short additional branches from base, ventral side of each segment) in male; filiform in female. Forewing length: 
<specimenCount box="[1072,1097,830,853]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
<specimenCount box="[1097,1114,830,853]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
<quantity box="[1128,1258,829,854]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" unit="mm" value="15.0" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="14.0">14–16 mm</quantity>
. Frons slightly protruding. Vertex usually pure white. Labial palpi slightly extending beyond frons. 
<emphasis box="[1154,1242,865,890]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Thorax.</emphasis>
Male hind tibia without spurs, not dilated and without hair-pencil in male, two pairs of spurs present in female. Frenulum well developed in both sexes. Forewing with apex pointed, hind wing with apex rounded. Postmedial line wavy. Discal spots on fore- and hind wings usually black and faint. 
<emphasis box="[766,872,974,997]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Venation.</emphasis>
Forewing with one or two areoles within species; veins R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[238,262,1024,1038]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">2–4</subScript>
always from apical angle of areole, veins R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[778,786,1024,1038]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">1</subScript>
and R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[864,872,1024,1038]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">5</subScript>
distally or directly from apex; veins R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1326,1334,1024,1038]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">5</subScript>
and R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1413,1436,1024,1038]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">2–4</subScript>
sometimes shortly stalked. Vein M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[544,552,1063,1077]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">2</subScript>
closer to M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[691,699,1063,1077]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">1</subScript>
; Veins M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[810,818,1063,1077]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">3</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[927,935,1063,1077]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">1</subScript>
unstalked. Hind wing with veins Rs and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1428,1436,1063,1077]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">1</subScript>
usually short-stalked, sometimes separate and from apical of discal cell; M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[988,996,1102,1116]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">3</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1103,1111,1102,1116]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">1</subScript>
separated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,793,1918]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">
<emphasis box="[199,305,1128,1153]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Abdomen</emphasis>
. Male 8 
<superScript attach="left" box="[407,419,1125,1139]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">th</superScript>
tergite with posterior margin concave and forming a pair of narrow spine-like lateral processes. Male 8 
<superScript attach="left" box="[356,368,1164,1178]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">th</superScript>
sternite with anterior margin strongly concave, cerata horn-like, arising from ventral side of mappa, mappa rounded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,793,1918]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">
<emphasis box="[199,371,1239,1264]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Male genitalia.</emphasis>
Uncus and gnathos absent. Socii composed of a pair of small processes. Tegumen with one or two pairs of processes on inner margin. Valvula and sacculus separate. Juxta quadrate with a pair of lateral lobes. Coremata present (easily lost during preparation). Saccus concave medially. Aedeagus strongly curved; vesica with a small patch of tiny spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,793,1918]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">
<emphasis box="[199,400,1383,1408]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Female genitalia.</emphasis>
Papillae anales rounded. Lamella antevaginalis well developed; lamella postvaginalis not developed. Ostium sclerotized. Ductus bursae narrow. Corpus bursae large and elongate; signum with a patch of small and scobinate sclerites, pointing away from longitudinal axis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="432" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,793,1918]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1491,1516]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The male antennae in 
<taxonomicName authority="Cui &amp; Xue &amp; Jiang, 2018" authorityName="Cui &amp; Xue &amp; Jiang" authorityYear="2018" box="[591,727,1491,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Aquilargilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="435" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[591,727,1491,1516]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Aquilargilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sub-quadripectinate and uncommon in the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duponchel" authorityYear="1845" box="[1321,1431,1491,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Scopulini">Scopulini</taxonomicName>
, which is similar to 
<emphasis box="[369,557,1527,1552]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Ideae serpentata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hufnagel, J. S." box="[573,751,1527,1552]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" pagination="504 - 527" refId="ref3597" refString="Hufnagel, J. S. (1767) Fortsetzung der Tabelle von den Nachtvogeln, welche die 3 te Art derselben, nehmlich die Spannenmesser (Phalaenas Geometras Linnaei) enthalt. Berlinisches Magazin, oder gesammlete Schriften und Nachrichten fur die Liebhaber der Arzneywissenschaft, Naturgeschichte und der angenehmen. Wissenschaften Uberhaupt, 4, 504 - 527." type="journal article" year="1767">Hüfnagel, 1767</bibRefCitation>
) of the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1892" box="[900,1001,1527,1552]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Sterrhini">Sterrhini</taxonomicName>
, but the rami in 
<taxonomicName authority="Cui &amp; Xue &amp; Jiang, 2018" authorityName="Cui &amp; Xue &amp; Jiang" authorityYear="2018" box="[1188,1324,1527,1552]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Aquilargilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="435" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1188,1324,1527,1552]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Aquilargilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are much longer. The posterior margin of the male 8 
<superScript attach="left" box="[623,635,1563,1577]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">th</superScript>
tergite in 
<taxonomicName authority="Cui &amp; Xue &amp; Jiang, 2018" authorityName="Cui &amp; Xue &amp; Jiang" authorityYear="2018" box="[748,884,1566,1591]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Aquilargilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="435" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[748,884,1566,1591]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Aquilargilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is concave and forms a pair of lateral spines; this character is also present in the 
<typeStatus box="[502,550,1603,1627]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">type</typeStatus>
species of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1888" box="[793,913,1602,1627]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Dithalama" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[793,913,1602,1627]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Dithalama</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick, 1888" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1888" box="[930,1269,1602,1627]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Dithalama" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cosmospila">
<emphasis box="[930,1091,1602,1627]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">D. cosmospila</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Meyrick, E." box="[1099,1269,1602,1627]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" pagination="621 - 1113" refId="ref3730" refString="Meyrick, E. (1888) Revision of Australian Lepidoptera. Proceedings of the Linnean Society of New South Wales, 2, 621 - 1113." type="journal article" year="1888">Meyrick, 1888</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
). The shape of the male 8 
<superScript attach="left" box="[270,282,1637,1651]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">th</superScript>
sternite in 
<taxonomicName authority="Cui &amp; Xue &amp; Jiang, 2018" authorityName="Cui &amp; Xue &amp; Jiang" authorityYear="2018" box="[411,547,1640,1665]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Aquilargilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="435" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[411,547,1640,1665]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Aquilargilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duponchel" authorityYear="1845" box="[740,850,1640,1665]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Scopulini">Scopulini</taxonomicName>
, as the anterior margin is strongly concave, and the cerata are present, arising from the ventral side of the mappa. In the male genitalia, the processes on the inner side of the tegumen in 
<taxonomicName authority="Cui &amp; Xue &amp; Jiang, 2018" authorityName="Cui &amp; Xue &amp; Jiang" authorityYear="2018" box="[360,496,1712,1737]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Aquilargilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="435" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[360,496,1712,1737]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Aquilargilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are atypical but not unique among the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duponchel" authorityYear="1845" box="[945,1055,1712,1737]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Scopulini">Scopulini</taxonomicName>
, as a similar structure is found in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Leech, 1897)" authorityName="Leech" authorityYear="1897" baseAuthorityName="Leech" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[151,561,1749,1774]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Somatina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mendicaria">
<emphasis box="[151,394,1749,1774]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Somatina mendicaria</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Leech, J. H." box="[410,553,1749,1774]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" pagination="65 - 111" refId="ref3805" refString="Leech, J. H. (1897) On Lepidoptera Heterocera from China, Japan, and Corea. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 6, 20 (116), 65 - 111 + 228 - 248. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222939708680620" type="journal article" year="1897">Leech, 1897</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1888" box="[620,740,1749,1774]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Dithalama" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[620,740,1749,1774]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Dithalama</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The juxta in 
<taxonomicName authority="Cui &amp; Xue &amp; Jiang, 2018" authorityName="Cui &amp; Xue &amp; Jiang" authorityYear="2018" box="[904,1040,1749,1774]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Aquilargilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="435" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[904,1040,1749,1774]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Aquilargilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duponchel" authorityYear="1845" box="[1237,1347,1749,1774]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="432" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Scopulini">Scopulini</taxonomicName>
, as it is quadrate with a pair of lateral lobes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="432" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,793,1918]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1821,1846]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic name is derived from the Latin dark (aquilus-) and clay (argilla), corresponding to the dark colour of the wings of the 
<typeStatus box="[503,551,1857,1881]" pageId="1" pageNumber="432">type</typeStatus>
species. The name is to be regarded as feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
